+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018gLvZtyPdW1cfWdGoaDogw","type":"tool_result","content":"The file /workspace/src/ws.ts has been updated successfully."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1200fcd-d534-41e0-a6ea-ae485dd4b49b","uuid":"be48781e-c57e-4ada-a30f-9a45b3a18e40","tool_use_result":{"filePath":"/workspace/src/ws.ts","oldString":"    if (clientVersion < 0 || clientVersion > state.version) {","newString":"    if (clientVersion < 1 || clientVersion > state.version) {","originalFile":"import { WebSocketServer, WebSocket } from 'ws';\nimport type { Server as HttpServer } from 'http';\nimport type { DocumentDB } from './db.js';\nimport { apply, transform, validate, type Operation } from './ot.js';\nimport { randomUUID } from 'crypto';\n\n/**\n * Message types from client to server:\n * - { type: 'operation', version: number, operation: Operation }\n *\n * Message types from server to client:\n * - { type: 'sync', content: string, version: number }\n * - { type: 'operation', operation: Operation, version: number, clientId: string }\n * - { type: 'ack', version: number }\n * - { type: 'error', message: string }\n */\n\ninterface ClientConnection {\n  ws: WebSocket;\n  clientId: string;\n  documentId: string;\n}\n\ninterface DocumentState {\n  version: number;\n  content: string;\n  /** Operations since version 1. Index i = operation that produced version i+1. */\n  operations: Operation[];\n  clients: Map<string, ClientConnection>;\n}\n\nexport class CollaborationServer {\n  private wss: WebSocketServer;\n  private documents: Map<string, DocumentState> = new Map();\n  private db: DocumentDB;\n\n  constructor(server: HttpServer, db: DocumentDB) {\n    this.db = db;\n    this.wss = new WebSocketServer({ noServer: true });\n\n    server.on('upgrade', (request, socket, head) => {\n      const url = new URL(request.url || '/', `http://${request.headers.host || 'localhost'}`);\n      const match = url.pathname.match(/^\\/documents\\/([^/]+)\\/ws$/);\n\n      if (!match) {\n        socket.destroy();\n        return;\n      }\n\n      const documentId = match[1];\n      const doc = this.db.getDocument(documentId);\n      if (!doc) {\n        socket.write('HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found\\r\\n\\r\\n');\n        socket.destroy();\n        return;\n      }\n\n      this.wss.handleUpgrade(request, socket, head, (ws) => {\n        this.handleConnection(ws, documentId);\n      });\n    });\n  }\n\n  private getOrCreateDocumentState(documentId: string): DocumentState {\n    let state = this.documents.get(documentId);\n    if (!state) {\n      const doc = this.db.getDocument(documentId);\n      if (!doc) throw new Error(`Document ${documentId} not found`);\n\n      const version = this.db.getLatestVersion(documentId);\n      // Load stored operations for transformation\n      const versions = this.db.getVersionHistory(documentId);\n      const operations: Operation[] = [];\n      for (const v of versions) {\n        if (v.operation) {\n          try {\n            const parsed = JSON.parse(v.operation);\n            if (Array.isArray(parsed)) {\n              operations.push(parsed);\n            }\n          } catch {\n            // Skip malformed operations\n          }\n        }\n      }\n\n      state = {\n        version,\n        content: doc.content,\n        operations,\n        clients: new Map(),\n      };\n      this.documents.set(documentId, state);\n    }\n    return state;\n  }\n\n  private handleConnection(ws: WebSocket, documentId: string): void {\n    const clientId = randomUUID();\n    const state = this.getOrCreateDocumentState(documentId);\n\n    const conn: ClientConnection = { ws, clientId, documentId };\n    state.clients.set(clientId, conn);\n\n    // Send sync message with current state\n    this.send(ws, {\n      type: 'sync',\n      content: state.content,\n      version: state.version,\n      clientId,\n    });\n\n    ws.on('message', (data) => {\n      try {\n        const message = JSON.parse(data.toString());\n        this.handleMessage(conn, message);\n      } catch (err) {\n        this.send(ws, {\n          type: 'error',\n          message: err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Invalid message',\n        });\n      }\n    });\n\n    ws.on('close', () => {\n      state.clients.delete(clientId);\n      if (state.clients.size === 0) {\n        // Keep state in memory for quick reconnection, don't clean up immediately\n      }\n    });\n\n    ws.on('error', () => {\n      state.clients.delete(clientId);\n    });\n  }\n\n  private handleMessage(\n    conn: ClientConnection,\n    message: { type: string; version?: number; operation?: Operation },\n  ): void {\n    if (message.type !== 'operation') {\n      this.send(conn.ws, {\n        type: 'error',\n        message: `Unknown message type: ${message.type}`,\n      });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    const state = this.documents.get(conn.documentId);\n    if (!state) {\n      this.send(conn.ws, { type: 'error', message: 'Document not found' });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    if (typeof message.version !== 'number') {\n      this.send(conn.ws, { type: 'error', message: 'Version is required' });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    if (!Array.isArray(message.operation)) {\n      this.send(conn.ws, { type: 'error', message: 'Operation is required and must be an array' });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    const clientVersion = message.version;\n    let operation = message.operation;\n\n    // The client's operation was based on version clientVersion.\n    // We need to transform it against all operations from clientVersion to current version.\n    if (clientVersion < 0 || clientVersion > state.version) {\n      this.send(conn.ws, {\n        type: 'error',\n        message: `Invalid version ${clientVersion}. Current version is ${state.version}`,\n      });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    // Transform against concurrent operations\n    // state.operations[i] took version (i+1) to version (i+2)\n    // Client at version v needs transforms against operations[v-1], operations[v], ...\n    const startIdx = clientVersion - 1;\n    for (let i = startIdx; i < state.operations.length; i++) {\n      const serverOp = state.operations[i];\n      try {\n        const [transformedClient] = transform(operation, serverOp);\n        operation = transformedClient;\n      } catch (err) {\n        this.send(conn.ws, {\n          type: 'error',\n          message: `Transform failed: ${err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'unknown error'}`,\n        });\n        return;\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Validate the transformed operation against current content\n    const validationError = validate(operation, state.content.length);\n    if (validationError) {\n      this.send(conn.ws, { type: 'error', message: validationError });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    // Apply the operation\n    let newContent: string;\n    try {\n      newContent = apply(state.content, operation);\n    } catch (err) {\n      this.send(conn.ws, {\n        type: 'error',\n        message: `Apply failed: ${err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'unknown error'}`,\n      });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    // Persist to database\n    const newVersion = this.db.updateDocumentContent(\n      conn.documentId,\n      newContent,\n      JSON.stringify(operation),\n    );\n\n    // Update in-memory state\n    state.operations.push(operation);\n    state.content = newContent;\n    state.version = newVersion;\n\n    // Send ack to the sender\n    this.send(conn.ws, { type: 'ack', version: newVersion });\n\n    // Broadcast to other clients\n    for (const [cid, client] of state.clients) {\n      if (cid !== conn.clientId && client.ws.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {\n        this.send(client.ws, {\n          type: 'operation',\n          operation,\n          version: newVersion,\n          clientId: conn.clientId,\n        });\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  private send(ws: WebSocket, message: object): void {\n    if (ws.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {\n      ws.send(JSON.stringify(message));\n    }\n  }\n\n  closeAll(): void {\n    for (const [, state] of this.documents) {\n      for (const [, client] of state.clients) {\n        client.ws.close();\n      }\n    }\n    this.documents.clear();\n    this.wss.close();\n  }\n}\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":167,"oldLines":7,"newStart":167,"newLines":7,"lines":[" ","     // The client's operation was based on version clientVersion.","     // We need to transform it against all operations from clientVersion to current version.","-    if (clientVersion < 0 || clientVersion > state.version) {","+    if (clientVersion < 1 || clientVersion > state.version) {","       this.send(conn.ws, {","         type: 'error',","         message: `Invalid version ${clientVersion}. Current version is ${state.version}`,"]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018kXQwCQz7GrBSukQA72hdE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me also think about the test that was failing. In the test:\n1. ws1 sends op1 at version 1, gets ack (version 2)\n2. ws2 sends op2 at version 1 (hasn't seen ws1's change)\n3. Server transforms op2 against op1\n\nWith `startIdx = 1 - 1 = 0`, and `state.operations.length = 1` (contains op1), the loop iterates once, transforming op2 against op1. This should work now.\n\nBut the test was timing out. Let me check if there's a problem with ws2 receiving the broadcast operation before we set up the ack listener. The issue is that ws2 receives the broadcast of ws1's operation. Then when we do `waitForMessage(ws2, 'ack')`, the listener is correctly filtering for 'ack'. But the problem might be that ws2's message handler from `waitForMessage` was not yet set up when the server sends back the ack, since JavaScript is single-threaded and we're awaiting ack1Promise first.\n\nActually no, the flow is:\n1. `ws1.send(op1)` \n2. `await ack1Promise` - this resolves when ws1 gets ack\n3. During this await, ws2 might receive the broadcast (operation message). It goes to the buffer.\n4. `const ack2Promise = waitForMessage(ws2, 'ack')` - sets up listener \n5. `ws2.send(op2)` \n6. `await ack2Promise` - waits for ack\n\nThe issue is step 3-4. If ws2 already received and buffered messages before step 4, the listener in step 4 won't see buffered messages. But Node.js WebSocket doesn't have a buffer for message events like that - if there's no listener, the 'message' event is emitted and lost. But wait, ws2 still has the original listener from `connectWs` removed? No, `connectWs` resolves after getting the sync message but it removes the listener (since it's within the promise). Actually looking at `connectWs`:\n\n```js\nws.on('message', (data) => {\n  const msg = JSON.parse(data.toString());\n  if (msg.type === 'sync') {\n    resolve({ ws, sync: msg });\n  }\n});\n```\n\nThis listener is NEVER removed! It stays attached. So when ws2 receives the broadcast, this listener fires but does nothing (it's not a 'sync' message). But it doesn't prevent other listeners from also receiving it. The issue is that there's no handler eating messages. The 'message' event fires and all listeners get it.\n\nSo when ws2 receives the broadcast of ws1's operation, the old sync handler fires (does nothing useful), and if `waitForMessage` handler is also attached, it would also fire. But we only attach `waitForMessage` for ack AFTER awaiting ack1Promise.\n\nThe key question is: does the broadcast message arrive at ws2 DURING the await of ack1Promise, or AFTER step 4?\n\nSince everything happens on the same event loop in this test setup (same process), the server processes ws1's message synchronously (it's a synchronous handler), broadcasts to ws2, and the ack goes to ws1. All of this happens in a single tick. The ws2.on('message') for the broadcast fires in the next microtask/event loop tick.\n\nAfter `await ack1Promise` resolves (ws1 got ack), the event loop continues. Now the broadcast message for ws2 might be queued. When we do `waitForMessage(ws2, 'ack')`, we set up a new listener. Then when `ws2.send(op2)` is called, the server processes it.\n\nBut the broadcast message to ws2 (from ws1's operation) might fire before the ack to ws2 (from ws2's operation). The `waitForMessage` handler correctly filters for 'ack', so it should skip the 'operation' message and wait for the 'ack'.\n\nHmm, but there might be an issue where the operation message for ws2 is delivered between step 4 and 6, causing the handler to be called but not match. Then the ack arrives and the handler is called again and matches. This should work...\n\nLet me rebuild and test to see if my index fix is enough:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":239,"cache_read_input_tokens":5